# 6. How to Become Strong at Arrays

---

# A. Practice Pattern Wise

Wrong:
random questions.

Correct:

* solve 15 sliding window questions together,
* then 15 two pointer questions,
* then prefix sum, etc.

This builds pattern intuition.

---

# B. Re-solve Problems

One problem solved deeply:
better than 20 shallow solutions.

---

# C. Focus on Optimization

Always ask:
“How do I reduce nested loops?”

---

# D. Learn to Read Constraints

Constraints reveal intended complexity.

Example:

| Constraint | Expected Complexity |
| ---------- | ------------------- |
| n <= 10³   | O(n²) possible      |
| n <= 10⁵   | O(n log n) or O(n)  |

---

# E. Dry Run Before Coding

Track:

* pointers,
* window,
* variables,
* conditions.

Most bugs are logical, not syntax-related.

---

# 7. How Experts Solve Unseen Questions

Experts do NOT memorize exact problems.

They:

1. classify problem,
2. identify pattern,
3. apply known framework.

This is why pattern mastery matters more than quantity.

